# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tree-shaking
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] In compiler theory, **dead-code elimination** (**DCE**, **dead-code removal**, **dead-code stripping**, or **dead-code strip**) is a compiler optimization to remove dead code (code that does not affect the program results).
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Removing such code has several benefits: it shrinks program size (an important consideration in some contexts); reduces resource usage, such as the number of bytes to be transferred; and allows the running program to avoid executing irrelevant operations, which reduces its running time.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] It can also enable further optimizations by simplifying program structure.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Dead code includes code that can never be executed (unreachable code) and code that only affects dead variables (written to, but never read again), that is, irrelevant to the program.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Consider the following example written in C.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Simple analysis of the uses of values would show that the value of `b` after the first assignment is not used inside `foo`.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Furthermore, `b` is declared as a local variable inside `foo`, so its value cannot be used outside `foo`.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Thus, the variable `b` is *dead* and an optimizer can reclaim its storage space and eliminate its initialization.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Furthermore, because the first return statement is executed unconditionally and there is no label after it which a "goto" could reach, no feasible execution path reaches the second assignment to `b`.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Thus, the assignment is *unreachable* and can be removed.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] If the procedure had a more complex control flow, such as a label after the return statement and a `goto` elsewhere in the procedure, then a feasible execution path might exist to the assignment to `b`.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Also, even though some calculations are performed in the function, their values are not stored in locations accessible outside the scope of this function.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Furthermore, given the function returns a static value (96), it may be simplified to the value it returns (this simplification is called constant folding).
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Most advanced compilers have options to activate dead-code elimination, sometimes at varying levels.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] A lower level might only remove instructions that cannot be executed.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] A higher level might also not reserve space for unused variables.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] A yet higher level might determine instructions or functions that serve no purpose and eliminate them.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] A common use of dead-code elimination is as an alternative to optional code inclusion via a preprocessor.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Because the constant `DEBUG_MODE` will always evaluate to false (due to being defined as so), the code inside the if statement can never be executed, and dead-code elimination would remove it entirely from the optimized program.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] This technique is common in debugging to optionally activate blocks of code; using an optimizer with dead-code elimination eliminates the need for using a preprocessor to perform the same task.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] In practice, much of the dead code that an optimizer finds is created by other transformations in the optimizer.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] For example, the classic techniques for operator strength reduction insert new computations into the code and render the older, more expensive computations dead.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Subsequent dead-code elimination removes those calculations and completes the effect (without complicating the strength-reduction algorithm).
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Historically, dead-code elimination was performed using information derived from data-flow analysis.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] An algorithm based on static single-assignment form (SSA) appears in the original journal article on *SSA* form by Ron Cytron et al.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Robert Shillingsburg (aka Shillner) improved on the algorithm and developed a companion algorithm for removing useless control-flow operations.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Dead code is normally considered dead *unconditionally*.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Therefore, it is reasonable attempting to remove dead code through dead-code elimination at compile time.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] However, in practice it is also common for code sections to represent dead or unreachable code only *under certain conditions*, which may not be known at the time of compilation or assembly.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Also, the software (for example, a driver or resident service) may be configurable to include or exclude certain features depending on user preferences, rendering unused code portions useless in a particular scenario.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] The techniques used to dynamically detect demand, identify and resolve dependencies, remove such conditionally dead code, and to recombine the remaining code at load or runtime are called **dynamic dead-code elimination** or **dynamic dead-instruction elimination**.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] However, language implementations doing just-in-time compilation may dynamically optimize for dead-code elimination.
[src:tree-shaking/dead-code-elimination] Although with a rather different focus, similar approaches are sometimes also utilized for dynamic software updating and hot patching.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This guide gives you all you need to get started with JavaScript module syntax.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] JavaScript programs started off pretty small — most of its usage in the early days was to do isolated scripting tasks, providing a bit of interactivity to your web pages where needed, so large scripts were generally not needed.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Fast forward a few years and we now have complete applications being run in browsers with a lot of JavaScript, as well as JavaScript being used in other contexts (Node.js, for example).
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Complex projects necessitate a mechanism for splitting JavaScript programs into separate modules that can be imported when needed.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Node.js has had this ability for a long time, and there are a number of JavaScript libraries and frameworks that enable module usage (for example, other CommonJS and AMD-based module systems like RequireJS, webpack, and Babel).
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] All modern browsers support module features natively without needing transpilation.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] It can only be a good thing — browsers can optimize loading of modules, making it more efficient than having to use a library and do all of that extra client-side processing and extra round trips.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] It does not obsolete bundlers like webpack, though — bundlers still do a good job at partitioning code into reasonably sized chunks, and are able to do other optimizations like minification, dead code elimination, and tree-shaking.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] To demonstrate usage of modules, we've created a set of examples that you can find on GitHub.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] These examples demonstrate a set of modules that create a `<canvas>` element on a webpage, and then draw (and report information about) different shapes on the canvas.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] These are fairly trivial, but have been kept deliberately simple to demonstrate modules clearly.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Throughout this article, we've used `.js` extensions for our module files, but in other resources you may see the `.mjs` extension used instead.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] V8's documentation recommends this, for example.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] However, we decided to keep using `.js`, at least for the moment.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] To get modules to work correctly in a browser, you need to make sure that your server is serving them with a `Content-Type` header that contains a JavaScript MIME type such as `text/javascript`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] If you don't, you'll get a strict MIME type checking error along the lines of "The server responded with a non-JavaScript MIME type" and the browser won't run your JavaScript.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Most servers already set the correct type for `.js` files, but not yet for `.mjs` files.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Servers that already serve `.mjs` files correctly include GitHub Pages and `http-server` for Node.js.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This is OK if you are using such an environment already, or if you aren't but you know what you are doing and have access (i.e., you can configure your server to set the correct `Content-Type` for `.mjs` files).
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] It could however cause confusion if you don't control the server you are serving files from, or are publishing files for public use, as we are here.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] For learning and portability purposes, we decided to keep to `.js`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] If you really value the clarity of using `.mjs` for modules versus using `.js` for "normal" JavaScript files, but don't want to run into the problem described above, you could always use `.mjs` during development and convert them to `.js` during your build step.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The first thing you do to get access to module features is export them.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This is done using the `export` statement.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You can export functions, `var`, `let`, `const`, and — as we'll see later — classes.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] They need to be top-level items: for example, you can't use `export` inside a function.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] A more convenient way of exporting all the items you want to export is to use a single export statement at the end of your module file, followed by a comma-separated list of the features you want to export wrapped in curly braces.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Once you've exported some features out of your module, you need to import them into your script to be able to use them.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You use the `import` statement, followed by a comma-separated list of the features you want to import wrapped in curly braces, followed by the keyword `from`, followed by the *module specifier*.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The *module specifier* provides a string that the JavaScript environment can resolve to a path to the module file.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In a browser, this could be a path relative to the site root, which for our `basic-modules` example would be `/js-examples/module-examples/basic-modules`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] However, here we are instead using the dot (`.`) syntax to mean "the current location", followed by the relative path to the file we are trying to find.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This is much better than writing out the entire absolute path each time, as relative paths are shorter and make the URL portable — the example will still work if you move it to a different location in the site hierarchy.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You can see such lines in action in `main.js`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Once you've imported the features into your script, you can use them just like they were defined inside the same file.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Import maps allow developers to instead specify almost any text they want in the module specifier when importing a module; the map provides a corresponding value that will replace the text when the module URL is resolved.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] For example, the `imports` key in the import map below defines a "module specifier map" JSON object where the property names can be used as module specifiers, and the corresponding values will be substituted when the browser resolves the module URL.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The values must be absolute or relative URLs.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Relative URLs are resolved to absolute URL addresses using the base URL of the document containing the import map.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The import map is defined using a JSON object inside a `<script>` element with the `type` attribute set to `importmap`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Note that an import map only applies to the document — the specification does not cover how to apply an import map in a worker or worklet context.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] With this map you can now use the property names above as module specifiers.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] If there is no trailing forward slash on the module specifier key then the whole module specifier key is matched and substituted.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] For example, below we match bare module names, and remap a URL to another path.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] If the module specifier has a trailing forward slash then the value must have one as well, and the key is matched as a "path prefix".
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This allows remapping of whole classes of URLs.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] It is possible for multiple keys in an import map to be valid matches for a module specifier.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] For example, a module specifier of `shapes/circle/` could match the module specifier keys `shapes/` and `shapes/circle/`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In this case the browser will select the most specific (longest) matching module specifier key.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Import maps allow modules to be imported using bare module names (as in Node.js), and can also simulate importing modules from packages, both with and without file extensions.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] While not shown above, they also allow particular versions of a library to be imported, based on the path of the script that is importing the module.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Generally they let developers write more ergonomic import code, and make it easier to manage the different versions and dependencies of modules used by a site.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This can reduce the effort required to use the same JavaScript libraries in both browser and server.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The following sections expand on the various features outlined above.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In some JavaScript environments, such as Node.js, you can use bare names for the module specifier.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This works because the environment can resolve module names to a standard location in the file system.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] For example, you might use the following syntax to import the "square" module.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] To use bare names on a browser you need an import map, which provides the information needed by the browser to resolve module specifiers to URLs (JavaScript will throw a `TypeError` if it attempts to import a module specifier that can't be resolved to a module location).
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Below you can see a map that defines a `square` module specifier key, which in this case maps to a relative address value.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Module specifier map entries, where both the specifier key and its associated value have a trailing forward slash (`/`), can be used as a path-prefix.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This allows the remapping of a whole set of import URLs from one location to another.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] It can also be used to emulate working with "packages and modules", such as you might see in the Node ecosystem.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] It is possible to import `fp` above without the `.js` file extension, but you would need to create a bare module specifier key for that file, such as `lodash/fp`, rather than using the path.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This may be reasonable for just one module, but scales poorly if you wish to import many modules.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] A module specifier key doesn't have to be path — it can also be an absolute URL (or a URL-like relative path like `./`, `../`, `/`).
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This may be useful if you want to remap a module that has absolute paths to a resource with your own local resources.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Ecosystems like Node use package managers such as npm to manage modules and their dependencies.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The package manager ensures that each module is separated from other modules and their dependencies.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] As a result, while a complex application might include the same module multiple times with several different versions in different parts of the module graph, users do not need to think about this complexity.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Import maps similarly allow you to have multiple versions of dependencies in your application and refer to them using the same module specifier.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You implement this with the `scopes` key, which allows you to provide module specifier maps that will be used depending on the path of the script performing the import.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] With this mapping, if a script with a URL that contains `/node_modules/dependency/` imports `cool-module`, the version in `/node_modules/some/other/location/cool-module/index.js` will be used.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The map in `imports` is used as a fallback if there is no matching scope in the scoped map, or the matching scopes don't contain a matching specifier.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] For example, if `cool-module` is imported from a script with a non-matching scope path, then the module specifier map in `imports` will be used instead, mapping to the version in `/node_modules/cool-module/index.js`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Note that the path used to select a scope does not affect how the address is resolved.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The value in the mapped path does not have to match the scopes path, and relative paths are still resolved to the base URL of the script that contains the import map.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Just as for module specifier maps, you can have many scope keys, and these may contain overlapping paths.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] If multiple scopes match the referrer URL, then the most specific scope path is checked first (the longest scope key) for a matching specifier.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The browsers will fall back to the next most specific matching scoped path if there is no matching specifier, and so on.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] If there is no matching specifier in any of the matching scopes, the browser checks for a match in the module specifier map in the `imports` key.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Script files used by websites often have hashed filenames to simplify caching.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The downside of this approach is that if a module changes, any modules that import it using its hashed filename will also need to be updated/regenerated.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This potentially results in a cascade of updates, which is wasteful of network resources.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Import maps provide a convenient solution to this problem.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Rather than depending on specific hashed filenames, applications and scripts instead depend on an un-hashed version of the module name (address).
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] An import map like the one below then provides a mapping to the actual script file.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] If `dependency_script` changes, then its hash contained in the file name changes as well.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In this case, we only need to update the import map to reflect the changed name of the module.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] We don't have to update the source of any JavaScript code that depends on it, because the specifier in the import statement does not change.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] One exciting feature that a unified module architecture brings is the ability to load non-JavaScript resources as modules.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] For example, you can import JSON as a JavaScript object, or import CSS as a `CSSStyleSheet` object.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You must explicitly declare what kind of resource you are importing.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] By default, the browser assumes that the resource is JavaScript, and will throw an error if the resolved resource is something else.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Browsers will also perform validation on the module type, and fail if, for example, `./data.json` does not resolve to a JSON file.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This ensures that you don't accidentally execute code when you just intend to import data.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Once imported successfully, you can now use the imported value as a normal JavaScript object or `CSSStyleSheet` object.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Now we just need to apply the `main.js` module to our HTML page.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This is very similar to how we apply a regular script to a page, with a few notable differences.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] First of all, you need to include `type="module"` in the `<script>` element, to declare this script as a module.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You can only use `import` and `export` statements inside modules, not regular scripts.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] An error will be thrown if your `<script>` element doesn't have the `type="module"` attribute and attempts to import other modules.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You should generally define all your modules in separate files.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Modules declared inline in HTML can only import other modules, but anything they export will not be accessible by other modules (because they don't have a URL).
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Module-defined variables are scoped to the module unless explicitly attached to the global object.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] On the other hand, globally-defined variables are available within the module.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The page would still render `Hello`, because the global variables `text` and `document` are available in the module.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The functionality we've exported so far has been comprised of **named exports** — each item (be it a function, `const`, etc.) has been referred to by its name upon export, and that name has been used to refer to it on import as well.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Let's look at an example as we explain how it works.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In our basic-modules `square.js` you can find a function called `randomSquare()` that creates a square with a random color, size, and position.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This is because there is only one default export allowed per module, and we know that `randomSquare` is it.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] So far, our canvas shape drawing modules seem to be working OK.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] But what happens if we try to add a module that deals with drawing another shape, like a circle or triangle?
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] These shapes would probably have associated functions like `draw()`, `reportArea()`, etc. too; if we tried to import different functions of the same name into the same top-level module file, we'd end up with conflicts and errors.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Fortunately there are a number of ways to get around this.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] We'll look at these in the following sections.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Inside your `import` and `export` statement's curly braces, you can use the keyword `as` along with a new feature name, to change the identifying name you will use for a feature inside the top-level module.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In our renaming directory you'll see the same module system as in the previous example, except that we've added `circle.js` and `triangle.js` modules to draw and report on circles and triangles.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The browser would throw an error such as "SyntaxError: redeclaration of import name" (Firefox).
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Note that you could solve the problem in the module files instead, e.g.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] What style you use is up to you, however it arguably makes more sense to leave your module code alone, and make the changes in the imports.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This especially makes sense when you are importing from third party modules that you don't have any control over.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The above method works OK, but it's a little messy and long-winded.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] An even better solution is to import each module's features inside a module object.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This grabs all the exports available inside `module.js`, and makes them available as members of an object `Module`, effectively giving it its own namespace.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] If you go to our module-objects directory, you'll see the same example again, but rewritten to take advantage of this new syntax.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] So you can now write the code just the same as before (as long as you include the object names where needed), and the imports are much neater.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] As we hinted at earlier, you can also export and import classes; this is another option for avoiding conflicts in your code, and is especially useful if you've already got your module code written in an object-oriented style.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You can see an example of our shape drawing module rewritten with ES classes in our classes directory.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] There will be times where you'll want to aggregate modules together.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You might have multiple levels of dependencies, where you want to simplify things, combining several submodules into one parent module.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] For an example, see our module-aggregation directory.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In this example (based on our earlier classes example) we've got an extra module called `shapes.js`, which aggregates all the functionality from `circle.js`, `square.js`, and `triangle.js` together.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] We've also moved our submodules inside a subdirectory inside the `modules` directory called `shapes`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In each of the submodules, the export is of the same form, e.g.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] These grab the exports from the individual submodules and effectively make them available from the `shapes.js` module.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] A recent addition to JavaScript modules functionality is dynamic module loading.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This allows you to dynamically load modules only when they are needed, rather than having to load everything up front.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This has some obvious performance advantages; let's read on and see how it works.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This new functionality allows you to call `import()` as a function, passing it the path to the module as a parameter.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] It returns a `Promise`, which fulfills with a module object (see Creating a module object) giving you access to that object's exports.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In the dynamic-module-imports directory we've got another example based on our classes example.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This time however we are not drawing anything on the canvas when the example loads.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Instead, we include three buttons — "Circle", "Square", and "Triangle" — that, when pressed, dynamically load the required module and then use it to draw the associated shape.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In this example we've only made changes to our `index.html` and `main.js` files — the module exports remain the same as before.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Note that, because the promise fulfillment returns a module object, the class is then made a subfeature of the object, hence we now need to access the constructor with `Module.` prepended to it, e.g., `Module.Square( /* … */ )`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Another advantage of dynamic imports is that they are always available, even in script environments.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Therefore, if you have an existing `<script>` tag in your HTML that doesn't have `type="module"`, you can still reuse code distributed as modules by dynamically importing it.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Top level await is a feature available within modules.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This means the `await` keyword can be used.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] It allows modules to act as big asynchronous functions meaning code can be evaluated before use in parent modules, but without blocking sibling modules from loading.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You can find all the files and code described in this section within the `top-level-await` directory, which extends from the previous examples.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Then we'll create a module called `getColors.js` which uses a fetch request to load the `colors.json` file and return the data as an object.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] We're using the keyword `await` before specifying the constant `colors` to export.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This means any other modules which include this one will wait until `colors` has been downloaded and parsed before using it.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This is useful because the code within `main.js` won't execute until the code in `getColors.js` has run.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] However it won't block other modules being loaded.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] For instance our `canvas.js` module will continue to load while `colors` is being fetched.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In this case, it means that the imported values are available in the module's code even before the place that declares them, and that the imported module's side effects are produced before the rest of the module's code starts running.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Still, it is considered good practice to put all your imports at the top of the code, which makes it easier to analyze dependencies.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Modules can import other modules, and those modules can import other modules, and so on.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This forms a directed graph called the "dependency graph".
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In an ideal world, this graph is acyclic.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In this case, the graph can be evaluated using a depth-first traversal.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Cyclic import arises if module `a` imports module `b`, but `b` directly or indirectly depends on `a`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The imported variable's value is only retrieved when the variable is actually used (hence allowing live bindings), and only if the variable remains uninitialized at that time will a `ReferenceError` be thrown.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In this example, both `a` and `b` are used asynchronously.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Therefore, at the time the module is evaluated, neither `b` nor `a` is actually read, so the rest of the code is executed as normal, and the two `export` declarations produce the values of `a` and `b`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Then, after the timeout, both `a` and `b` are available, so the two `console.log` statements also execute as normal.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This is because when JavaScript evaluates `a.js`, it needs to first evaluate `b.js`, the dependency of `a.js`.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] However, `b.js` uses `a`, which is not yet available.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] This is because the evaluation of `b.js` completes normally, so the value of `b` is available when `a.js` is evaluated.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] You should usually avoid cyclic imports in your project, because they make your code more error-prone.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] However, cyclic imports can also occur if the libraries depend on each other, which is harder to fix.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] The introduction of modules encourages the JavaScript ecosystem to distribute and reuse code in a modular fashion.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] However, that doesn't necessarily mean a piece of JavaScript code can run in every environment.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Suppose you discovered a module that generates SHA hashes of your user's password.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Can you use it in the browser front end?
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Modules still have access to global variables, as demonstrated previously.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] If the module references globals like `window`, it can run in the browser, but will throw an error in your Node.js server, because `window` is not available there.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Similarly, if the code requires access to `process` to be functional, it can only be used in Node.js.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] In order to maximize the reusability of a module, it is often advised to make the code "isomorphic" — that is, exhibits the same behavior in every runtime.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] These practices are not unique to modules.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Still, with the trend of code reusability and modularization, you are encouraged to make your code cross-platform so that it can be enjoyed by as many people as possible.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Runtimes like Node.js are also actively implementing web APIs where possible to improve interoperability with the web.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Here are a few tips that may help you if you are having trouble getting your modules to work.
[src:tree-shaking/guide-modules] Feel free to add to the list if you discover more!
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] Minification can be distinguished from the more general concept of data compression in that the minified source can be interpreted immediately without the need for a decompression step: the same interpreter can work with both the original as well as with the minified source.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] The goals of minification are not the same as the goals of obfuscation; the former is often intended to be reversed using a pretty printer or unminifier.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] However, to achieve its goals, minification sometimes uses techniques also used by obfuscation; for example, shortening variable names and refactoring the source code.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] When minification uses such techniques, the pretty-printer or unminifier can only fully reverse the minification process if it is supplied details of the transformations done by such techniques.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] If not supplied those details, the reversed source code will contain different variable names and control flow, even though it will have the same functionality as the original source code.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] In 2001 Douglas Crockford introduced JSMin, which removed comments and whitespace from JavaScript code.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] It was followed by YUI Compressor in 2007.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] In 2009, Google opened up its Closure toolkit, including Closure Compiler which contained a source mapping feature together with a Firefox extension called Closure Inspector.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] In 2010, Mihai Bazon introduced UglifyJS, which was superseded by UglifyJS2 in 2012; the rewrite was to allow for source map support.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] From 2017, Alex Lam took over maintenance and development of UglifyJS2, replacing it with UglifyJS3 which unified the CLI with the API.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] In 2018, Terser has been forked from uglify-es and has gained momentum since; in 2020 it outstripped UglifyJS when measured in daily downloads.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] Since late 2018, Terser has recommended the bundler RollupJS.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] A **source map** is a file format that allows software tools for JavaScript to display different code to a user than the code actually executed by the computer.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] For example, to aid in debugging of minified code, by "mapping" this code to the original unminified source code instead.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] The original format was created by Joseph Schorr as part of the Closure Inspector minification project.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] Version 2 and 3 of the format reduced the size of the map files considerably.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] In 2024, source maps were standardized by Ecma International's TC39 technical committee as ECMA-426.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] JavaScript and Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) resources may be minified, preserving their behavior while considerably reducing their file size.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] Libraries available online are capable of minification and optimization to varying degrees.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] Some libraries also merge multiple script files into a single file for client download.
[src:tree-shaking/minification-programming] JavaScript source maps can make code readable and debuggable even after it has been combined and minified.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] It’s been available across browsers since May 2018.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] The **`export`** declaration is used to export values from a JavaScript module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Exported values can then be imported into other programs with the `import` declaration or dynamic import.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] The value of an imported binding is subject to change in the module that exports it — when a module updates the value of a binding that it exports, the update will be visible in its imported value.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] In order to use the `export` declaration in a source file, the file must be interpreted by the runtime as a module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] In HTML, this is done by adding `type="module"` to the `<script>` tag, or by being imported by another module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Modules are automatically interpreted in strict mode.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Identifier to be exported (so that it can be imported via `import` in another script).
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] If you use an alias with `as`, the actual exported name can be specified as a string literal, which may not be a valid identifier.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Every module can have two different types of export, *named export* and *default export*.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] You can have multiple named exports per module but only one default export.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Each type corresponds to one of the above syntax.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] After the `export` keyword, you can use `let`, `const`, and `var` declarations, as well as function or class declarations.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] You can also use the `export { name1, name2 }` syntax to export a list of names declared elsewhere.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Note that `export {}` does not export an empty object — it's a no-op declaration that exports nothing (an empty name list).
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] You cannot use `export` on a `using` or `await using` declaration.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] You can, however, export a variable that was declared elsewhere using `using` or `await using`.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Doing so is still strongly discouraged, because the variable is disposed as soon as the module finishes executing, causing all importers to receive a value that's already disposed.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Export declarations are not subject to temporal dead zone rules.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] You can declare that the module exports `X` before the name `X` itself is declared.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] The `export default` syntax allows any expression.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] As a special case, functions and classes are exported as *declarations*, not expressions, and these declarations can be anonymous.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Named exports are useful when you need to export several values.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] When importing this module, named exports must be referred to by the exact same name (optionally renaming it with `as`), but the default export can be imported with any name.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] You can rename a name to something that's not a valid identifier by using a string literal.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] A module can also "relay" values exported from other modules without the hassle of writing two separate import/export statements.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] This is often useful when creating a single module concentrating various exports from various modules (usually called a "barrel module").
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Most of the "import from" syntaxes have "export from" counterparts.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] There is also `export * from "mod"`, although there's no `import * from "mod"`.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] This re-exports all **named** exports from `mod` as the named exports of the current module, but the default export of `mod` is not re-exported.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] If there are two wildcard exports statements that implicitly re-export the same name, neither one is re-exported.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] Attempting to import the duplicate name directly will throw an error.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-export] The "export from" syntax allows the `as` token to be omitted, which makes the default export still re-exported as default export.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The static **`import`** declaration is used to import read-only live bindings which are exported by another module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The imported bindings are called *live bindings* because they are updated by the module that exported the binding, but cannot be re-assigned by the importing module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] In order to use the `import` declaration in a source file, the file must be interpreted by the runtime as a module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] In HTML, this is done by adding `type="module"` to the `<script>` tag.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] There is also a function-like dynamic `import()`, which does not require scripts of `type="module"`.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Name that will refer to the default export from the module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Only single quoted and double quoted string literals are allowed.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The evaluation of the specifier is host-specified.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Most hosts align with browsers and resolve the specifiers as URLs relative to the current module URL (see `import.meta.url`).
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Node, bundlers, and other non-browser environments often define their own features on top of this, so you should find documentation for them to understand the exact rules.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The module specifier resolution section also has more information.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Name of the module object that will be used as a kind of namespace when referring to the imports.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The name can be either an identifier or a string literal, depending on what `module-name` declares to export.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] If it is a string literal, it must be aliased to a valid identifier.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Names that will refer to the named imports.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The `"module-name"` may be followed by a set of import attributes, starting with the `with` keyword.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] `import` declarations can only be present in modules, and only at the top-level (i.e., not inside blocks, functions, etc.).
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] If an `import` declaration is encountered in non-module contexts (for example, `<script>` tags without `type="module"`, `eval`, `new Function`, which all have "script" or "function body" as parsing goals), a `SyntaxError` is thrown.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] To load modules in non-module contexts, use the dynamic import syntax instead.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] All imported bindings cannot be in the same scope as any other declaration, including `let`, `const`, `class`, `function`, `var`, and `import` declaration.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] `import` declarations are designed to be syntactically rigid (for example, only string literal specifiers, only permitted at the top-level, all bindings must be identifiers), which allows modules to be statically analyzed and linked before getting evaluated.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] This is the key to making modules asynchronous by nature, powering features like top-level await.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Below are examples to clarify the syntax.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Given a value named `myExport` which has been exported from the module `my-module` either implicitly as `export * from "another.js"` or explicitly using the `export` statement, this inserts `myExport` into the current scope.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] You can import multiple names from the same module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] You can rename an export when importing it.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] For example, this inserts `shortName` into the current scope.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] A module may also export a member as a string literal which is not a valid identifier, in which case you must alias it in order to use it in the current module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Default exports need to be imported with the corresponding default import syntax.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Since the default export doesn't explicitly specify a name, you can give the identifier any name you like.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] It is also possible to specify a default import with namespace imports or named imports.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] In such cases, the default import will have to be declared first.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Importing a name called `default` has the same effect as a default import.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] It is necessary to alias the name because `default` is a reserved word.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The following code inserts `myModule` into the current scope, containing all the exports from the module located at `/modules/my-module.js`.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Here, `myModule` represents a *namespace* object which contains all exports as properties.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] `myModule` is a sealed object with `null` prototype.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The default export is available as a key called `default`.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] For more information, see module namespace object.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Import an entire module for side effects only, without importing anything.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] This runs the module's global code, but doesn't actually import any values.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] This is often used for polyfills, which mutate the global variables.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] In this case, that means that the identifiers the imports introduce are available in the entire module scope, and their side effects are produced before the rest of the module's code runs.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The ECMAScript specification does not define how module specifiers are resolved and leaves it to the host environment (e.g., browsers, Node.js, Deno).
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Browser behavior is specified by the HTML spec, and this has become the *de facto* baseline for all environments.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The most notable caveat for relative specifiers, especially for people familiar with the CommonJS conventions, is that browsers forbid one specifier to implicitly resolve to many potential candidates.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] On the web, this is costly because if you write `import x from "./utils"`, the browser needs to send requests to `utils`, `utils/index.js`, `utils.js`, and potentially many other URLs until it finds an importable module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Therefore, in the HTML spec, the specifier by default can only be a URL resolved relative to the current module URL.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] You cannot omit the file extension or the `index.js` file name.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] This behavior has been inherited by Node's ESM implementation, but it is not a part of the ECMAScript specification.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Note that this does not mean that `import x from "./utils"` never works on the web.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The browser still sends a request to that URL, and if the server can respond with the correct content, the import will succeed.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] This requires the server to implement some custom resolution logic, because usually extension-less requests are understood as requests for HTML files.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Absolute specifiers can be any kind of URL that resolve to importable source code.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Bare specifiers, popularized by CommonJS, are resolved within the `node_modules` directory.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] For example, if you have `import x from "foo"`, then the runtime will look for the `foo` package within any `node_modules` directory in the parent directories of the current module.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] This behavior can be reproduced in browsers using import maps, which also enable you to customize resolution in other ways.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The module resolution algorithm can also be executed programmatically using the `import.meta.resolve` function defined by the HTML spec.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] In this example, we create a re-usable module that exports a function to get all primes within a given range.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] The identifier being imported is a *live binding*, because the module exporting it may re-assign it and the imported value would change.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] However, the module importing it cannot re-assign it.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Still, any module holding an exported object can mutate the object, and the mutated value can be observed by all other modules importing the same value.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] You can also observe the new value through the module namespace object.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] Non-JavaScript modules can also be imported using the `import` statement, but their types need to be explicitly declared using import attributes.
[src:tree-shaking/statements-import] For example, to import a JSON module, you need to specify the `type: "json"` attribute.
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] In computing, **tree shaking** is a dead code elimination technique that is applied when optimizing code.
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] Often contrasted with traditional single-library dead code elimination techniques common to minifiers, tree shaking eliminates unused functions from across the bundle by starting at the entry point and only including functions that may be executed.
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] It is succinctly described as "live code inclusion".
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] Dead code elimination in dynamic languages is a much harder problem than in static languages.
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] The idea of a "treeshaker" originated in LISP in the 1990s.
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] The idea is that all possible execution flows of a program can be represented as a tree of function calls, so that functions that are never called can be eliminated.
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] The next wave of popularity of the term is attributed to Rich Harris's Rollup project developed in 2015.
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] The popularity of tree shaking in JavaScript is based on the fact that in contrast to CommonJS modules, ECMAScript 6 module loading is static and thus the whole dependency tree can be deduced by statically parsing the syntax tree.
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] Thus tree shaking becomes an easy problem.
[src:tree-shaking/tree-shaking] However, tree shaking does not only apply at the import/export level: it can also work at the statement level, depending on the implementation.
